---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
import SectionIntro from '../components/SectionIntro.astro';
import ContactCTA from '../components/ContactCTA.astro';
import projects from '../data/projects.json';

const featured = projects.slice(0, 5);
const productWork = projects.slice(5);
const pillars = [
  ['Designed objects', 'Commercial products and mechanisms resolved through use, manufacture, legibility and durability.'],
  ['Development systems', 'Ideas carried past sketch stage into testable, buildable propositions with real-world constraints.'],
  ['Project management', 'Budgets, programmes, contractors, clients and deadlines held together without losing the design intent.'],
  ['JungDesign', 'A professional practice built on noticing what is wrong, clarifying what is needed, and making the answer workable.']
];
---
<Layout title="Development — JungDesign" description="David Jung’s JungDesign development, design-management and project-management work.">
  <SectionIntro eyebrow="Development / Foundation" title="Sixty years of making ideas workable" intro="Before painting became the main daily practice, JungDesign was a working design and project-management practice: products, environments, systems, rollouts and commercial problem-solving."/>

  <section class="dev-manifesto">
    <div class="dev-manifesto-mark">JD</div>
    <div>
      <span class="eyebrow">Professional spine</span>
      <p>David Jung’s development work is not a side note to the paintings. It is the discipline underneath them: clear composition, practical judgement, careful sequencing, a feel for materials and a habit of turning vague problems into usable form.</p>
      <p>The archive below is deliberately text-first. It is not a dump of scanned documents; it is a curated record of the kind of commercial work JungDesign has led.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="career-pillars" aria-label="JungDesign development capabilities">
    {pillars.map(([title,copy],index)=><article>
      <b>{String(index+1).padStart(2,'0')}</b>
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      <p>{copy}</p>
    </article>)}
  </section>

  <section class="project-index" id="commercial-projects">
    <div class="project-index-intro">
      <span class="eyebrow">Commercial projects</span>
      <h2>Environments, rollouts, systems and objects.</h2>
      <p>These case studies are condensed from David’s project notes into a readable professional archive. They give the JungDesign name weight without distracting from the painting galleries.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="project-feature-grid">
      {featured.map((project)=><a class="project-tile feature" href={`/design/${project.slug}/`}>
        <figure class="project-source-image"><img src={project.image} alt={project.imageAlt} loading="lazy" decoding="async"/><figcaption>{project.visual.label}</figcaption></figure>
        <span>{project.number} / {project.type}</span>
        <h3>{project.title}</h3>
        <p>{project.summary}</p>
        <i>Read case study →</i>
      </a>)}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="project-index product-index">
    <div class="project-index-intro">
      <span class="eyebrow">Product development</span>
      <h2>Useful things, safer systems, better mechanisms.</h2>
      <p>Across product and system work, the pattern is consistent: define the friction, make the use clearer, and develop a response that can be manufactured, installed, trialled or operated.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="project-index-grid compact">
      {productWork.map((project)=><a class="project-tile text-only" href={`/design/${project.slug}/`}>
        <figure class="project-source-image"><img src={project.image} alt={project.imageAlt} loading="lazy" decoding="async"/><figcaption>{project.visual.label}</figcaption></figure>
        <span>{project.number} / {project.period}</span>
        <h3>{project.title}</h3>
        <p>{project.problem}</p>
        <i>Open project →</i>
      </a>)}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="career-spine">
    <span class="eyebrow">How to read this archive</span>
    <h2>Design here means responsibility.</h2>
    <p>Not just styling. Not just management. The recurring JungDesign move is to take responsibility for the whole chain: the object, the setting, the people using it, the money available, the deadline approaching and the detail that must still be right.</p>
  </section>

  <blockquote>“The paintings don’t leave design behind. They make its instincts visible.”</blockquote>
  <ContactCTA title="A design conversation?" copy="David welcomes selected design and project enquiries alongside questions about the paintings."/>
</Layout>
